  "text": "Alternatively, synapse-specific changes can occur through a synaptic tagging process. In the synaptic tag-and-capture mechanism of synapse-specific plasticity, first proposed by [CITATION_1] , a synaptic tag, temporarily present in a weakly stimulated postsynaptic site, links that synapse to the plasticity-inducing proteins that are translated at a strongly stimulated synapse. This hypothesis provides an explanation for why weak stimulation of a synapse does not induce protein synthesis, whereas strong stimulation of a neighboring synapse is sufficient to produce new proteins that appear selectively in the two stimulated synapses, but not in nearby synapses that received no stimulation at all. Evidence for this mechanism comes from the finding that induction of short-lasting LTP in one pathway with a weak stimulus results in longlasting LTP when it is paired with strong stimulation of a different synapse on the same neuron Morris, 1997, 1998) .",
